<Document>
<name>Million Dollar Highway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Million Dollar Highway</h2><p><i>Colorado, USA · US-550, Durango to Ouray</i></p><p><b>San Juan Mountains' jagged spine: 1880s mining road, no guardrails, three high passes.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>94 km (58 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3 hrs no stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–October</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>No guardrails on long stretches; blind switchbacks; winter avalanches; loaded RVs grinding uphill</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>250</td></tr></table><hr><p>Otto Mears built this as a toll road in the 1880s to serve the silver and gold mines of the San Juans. The 'Million Dollar' name has competing origin stories — that the per-mile construction cost was that high in 1880s dollars; that the gold-bearing fill used in resurfacing was worth a million; or that one early traveler said no one would drive it again for less. The 40 km between Silverton and Ouray, with their three 3,300+ m passes and absent guardrails, are the sphincter-tightening climax. Drive slow.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Molas Pass</b> — 3,326 m alpine bowl with Grenadier Range across the valley. Photographers' favorite — wildflowers in July, aspen gold in late September.</li><li><b>Silverton</b> — 1874 silver-mining town, gravel main streets preserved. Northern terminus of the Durango &amp; Silverton narrow-gauge steam railroad.</li><li><b>Red Mountain Pass</b> — 3,358 m. Iron oxide stains the surrounding peaks fluorescent orange. Avalanche country — dozens of named slide paths.</li><li><b>Ironton ghost town</b> — Late-19th-century mining camp ruins; weathered timbers and rust-colored mine tailings.</li><li><b>Bear Creek Falls</b> — 60 m falls drops from beneath the road right beside a turnout — no fence, just a step into the void.</li><li><b>Ouray</b> — 'Switzerland of America,' set in a box canyon. Hot springs pool downtown; world's largest collection of frozen-waterfall ice climbing in winter.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
